I am surprised Grace didn't correct this since she is a meteorologist, but humidity is relative to air temperature. If you heat a container of air without adding moisture, your humidity drops because humidity is how much moisture in the air relative to how much it can hold. At 78°F, the max in the flex seal tent, the air could hold up to 27g of water per cubic meter of air, whereas in the non sealed tent, the air at 64°F can hold 15.4g per cubic meter. If over night it got down to 25°F, the most the air could hold is 3.7g/m3.
78°F at 40% humidity has about the same moisture content (9.4 g/m3) as 63% RH at 64°F.
All that is to say, yes, higher humidity does make it feel more uncomfortable, but giving just a humidity level, doesn't give you how much moisture there actually is.
